      "description": "In 1992, Paul Mazurkiewicz had no cymbal endorsement deal. The Meinl partnership that defines his modern setup was years in the future. What he played on \"Tomb of the Mutilated\" was the era-typical working-band cymbal arsenal: a mix of Paiste 2002s, Paiste 502s, Zildjian A, or Zildjian ZBT cymbals — whatever combination of professional, semi-pro, and budget cymbals he could assemble and replace as cracks and bell separations took their toll across constant touring.\n\nThe 14\" hi-hats are the rhythmic anchor of the record. On the iconic groove of \"Hammer Smashed Face,\" the hi-hats sit just under the snare backbeat, driving the song's mid-tempo pulse with the kind of locked, unwavering eighth-note pattern that became the Cannibal Corpse rhythmic signature. In the blast passages, the hi-hats define the fast subdivision over the alternating kick-snare pattern — at extreme tempos, that articulation matters more than tonal sophistication.\n\nThe 16\" and 18\" crashes give Mazurkiewicz two accent voices for riff transitions. Death metal compositions live and die on tight, precise transitions between sections, and the crashes punctuate those changes without cluttering the mix.\n\nThe China cymbal is increasingly central across \"Tomb of the Mutilated.\" Mazurkiewicz uses it as a trashy accent for major riff transitions — its aggressive, fast-decay voice became a signature element of the Cannibal Corpse sound, and Burns mixed it forward enough to make those accents readable through the guitar density.\n\nScott Burns close-miked the cymbals individually rather than relying purely on overheads — the bleed-control approach that kept cymbal wash from blurring blast beat passages at extreme tempo. The overheads were positioned tight in an XY configuration to capture spatial information without dragging the room sound into the mix.",
