    "technique": {
      "title": "Conventional Grip, Locomotive Double-Bass: The Cannibal Corpse Percussive Identity",
      "content": "What separates Paul Mazurkiewicz from his peers in the early-90s Florida death metal scene — and what \"Tomb of the Mutilated\" captures most clearly — is his commitment to a specific philosophical and technical approach: brutality over flash, weight over speed, and a percussive identity built on choices that other death metal drummers had already abandoned.\n\n**Conventional (Traditional) Grip:**\nThe most distinctive single element of Mazurkiewicz's technique is his use of traditional (conventional) grip on the snare hand. In an era when nearly every death metal drummer had moved to matched grip for the symmetric power both hands required, Mazurkiewicz kept the angled, jazz-derived traditional grip he had developed early in his playing. The choice has trade-offs — traditional grip is harder to generate raw power with on heavy backbeats — but it gives him a specific feel and rhythmic articulation that has become inseparable from the Cannibal Corpse sound. The slight angle of the left stick on the snare head produces a particular stroke character that Mazurkiewicz built his entire vocabulary around.\n\n**The Locomotive Double-Bass:**\nMazurkiewicz's double-bass approach has been described as \"locomotive\" — relentless, powerful, locked to the grid, and built for sustained operation rather than peak velocity. On \"Tomb of the Mutilated,\" that approach is fully formed. Across \"Hammer Smashed Face,\" the double-bass anchors the song's mid-tempo groove with the kind of steam-engine inevitability that gave Cannibal Corpse their rhythmic identity. Across the faster passages of \"I Cum Blood\" and \"Necropedophile,\" the same locomotive philosophy applies at higher tempo — every kick stroke is deliberate, every double-kick passage feels like architecture rather than chaos.\n\n**The Blast Beat Approach:**\nMazurkiewicz plays the standard alternating blast (left foot, right hand, right foot, left hand) rather than the gravity-blast technique pioneered by drummers like Pete Sandoval. His blasts are not the fastest in death metal — they were never trying to be — but they are among the most consistent. Across an entire blast passage, every stroke lands with the same weight, the same timing, the same dynamic level. That consistency makes the blasts function as compositional architecture: a wall of percussion the guitar riffs can lean against rather than a sprint that demands attention to itself.\n\n**Serve-the-Riff Phrasing:**\nMazurkiewicz's playing on \"Tomb of the Mutilated\" demonstrates the philosophy that has defined his 35+ year career: the drums serve the riff, not the other way around. When Bob Rusay and Jack Owen write a tremolo passage, Mazurkiewicz locks in beneath it. When the riff transitions to a slower groove, the kit slows with it. There are no drum-centric showcase moments on the record — every fill, every roll, every cymbal accent is in service of making the songs hit harder. This philosophy made Cannibal Corpse the commercially leading death metal band rather than just the most extreme one, because the songs remain memorable as songs rather than as exhibitions of technique.\n\n**The Hammer Smashed Face Template:**\n\"Hammer Smashed Face\" became the most recognizable single in death metal history precisely because Mazurkiewicz's drumming gave it the architecture other death metal songs lacked. The iconic groove — that mid-tempo, swaggering pulse with the snare on 2 and 4 and the kicks locking with the riff — is built on disciplined restraint. A drummer aiming to impress would have filled the spaces between the snare hits with showy double-bass flurries. Mazurkiewicz left those spaces alone, because the song was better with them empty. That decision is the most important thing on the record."
    },
